Definition 4.2.1. The sets $\mathcal{E}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}^{\downarrow}$ and $\mathcal{E}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}^{\uparrow}$ are defined as follows, where each $s_{m}$ in the notation is a sink or source in $A_{\mathbb{R}}$ or one of $\pm\infty$ where appropriate: $\displaystyle\mathcal{E}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}^{\downarrow}:=$ $\displaystyle\left(\{x\in{\mathbb{R}}:\exists\text{ a sink and source }s_{2m}<% x<s_{2m+1}\}\cup\{|s_{2n-1},s_{2n}|\}\right)\times\{{-},{+}\}$ $\displaystyle\mathcal{E}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}^{\uparrow}:=$ $\displaystyle\left(\{x\in{\mathbb{R}}:\exists\text{ a source and sink }s_{2m-1% }<x<s_{2m}\}\cup\{|s_{2n},s_{2n+1}|\}\right)\times\{{-},{+}\}$ We write $\bar{a}$ to mean $(a,\varepsilon)$. That is, we are writing the first coordinate with an overline. Recall $-<+$ in $\{{-},{+}\}$. We define a total order on $\mathcal{E}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}^{\downarrow}$: • We say $(x,\varepsilon)<(y,\varepsilon^{\prime})$ if and only if $x<y$ or $x=y$ and $\varepsilon<\varepsilon^{\prime}$. • We say $(|s_{m},s_{m+1}|,\varepsilon)<(|s_{n},s_{n+1}|,\varepsilon^{\prime})$ if and only if $s_{m}<s_{n}$ or $s_{m}=s_{n}$ and $\varepsilon<\varepsilon^{\prime}$. • We say $(x,\varepsilon)<(|s_{m},s_{m+1}|,\varepsilon^{\prime})$ if and only if $x<s_{m}$. • We say $(|s_{m},s_{m+1}|,\varepsilon)<(y,\varepsilon^{\prime})$ if and only if $s_{m+1}<y$. We define a total order on $\mathcal{E}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}^{\uparrow}$ the same way. The set $\mathcal{E}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}^{\downarrow}$ has a maximal (respectively minimal) element if and only if $+\infty$ has an odd index (respectively $-\infty$ has an even index). Dually, $\mathcal{E}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}^{\uparrow}$ has a maximal (respectively minimal) element if and only if $+\infty$ has an even index (respectively $-\infty$ has an odd index). Let $\mathcal{E}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}=\mathcal{E}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}^{\downarrow}\cup% \mathcal{E}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}^{\uparrow}$.
Definition 2.4.2. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a Krull-Schmidt category and $\mathbf{P}$ a pairwise compatibility condition on $\text{Ind}(\mathcal{C})$ such that $\mathbf{P}$ induces the $\mathbf{P}$-cluster theory of $\mathcal{C}$. Assume the morphisms of $\mathscr{T}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{C})$, denoted $(\mathscr{T}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{C}))_{1}$, form a set. We define the set $\mathbf{P}(\mathcal{C})\subset(\mathscr{T}_{\mathbf{P}}(\mathcal{C}))_{1}$ to be the set containing all (trivial) $\mathbf{P}$-mutations. We give the set of $\mathbf{P}$-mutations a topology in the following way. Consider $[0,1]$ with the usual topology. A set $U\subset\mathbf{P}(\mathcal{C})$ is called open if, for all $p_{\overline{\mu}}:[0,1]\to\mathbf{P}(\mathcal{C})$ induced by a $\mathbf{P}$-mutation $\overline{\mu}$, $p_{\overline{\mu}}^{-1}(U)$ is open in $[0,1]$. We call $\mathbf{P}(\mathcal{C})$ the space of $\mathbf{P}$-mutations in $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 1.1.1. A quiver of continuous type $A$, denoted by $A_{\mathbb{R}}$, is a triple $({\mathbb{R}},S,\preceq)$, where: (1) (a) $S\subset{\mathbb{R}}$ is a discrete subset, possibly empty, with no accumulation points. (b) Order on $S\cup\{\pm\infty\}$ is induced by the order of ${\mathbb{R}}$, and $-\infty<s<+\infty$ for $\forall s\in S$. (c) Elements of $S\cup\{\pm\infty\}$ are indexed by a subset of ${\mathbb{Z}}\cup\{\pm\infty\}$ so that $s_{n}$ denotes the element of $S\cup\{\pm\infty\}$ with index $n$. The indexing must adhere to the following two conditions: i1 There exists $s_{0}\in S\cup\{\pm\infty\}$. i2 If $m\leq n\in{\mathbb{Z}}\cup\{\pm\infty\}$ and $s_{m},s_{n}\in S\cup\{\pm\infty\}$ then for all $p\in{\mathbb{Z}}\cup\{\pm\infty\}$ such that $m\leq p\leq n$ the element $s_{p}$ is in $S\cup\{\pm\infty\}$. (2) New partial order $\preceq$ on ${\mathbb{R}}$, which we call the orientation of $A_{\mathbb{R}}$, is defined as: p1 The $\preceq$ order between consecutive elements of $S\cup\{\pm\infty\}$ does not change. p2 Order reverses at each element of $S$. p3 If $n$ is even $s_{n}$ is a sink. p3’ If $n$ is odd $s_{n}$ is a source.
Definition 4.2.15. For any continuous quiver $A_{\mathbb{R}}$ of type $A$ we define $\mathcal{C}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}$ just as in Definition 4.1.7 except we replace $\mathcal{E}$ with $\mathcal{E}_{A_{\mathbb{R}}}$. Note again that each $\theta$ is in its own isomorphism class. We again say $\{\theta,\theta^{\prime}\}$ is $\mathbf{N}_{\overline{{\mathbb{R}}}}$-compatible if and only if $\operatorname{Hom}(\theta,\theta^{\prime})=0$ or $\theta=\theta^{\prime}$.
Definition 3. A Schreier split epimorphism in $\mathbf{RNMono}(\mathbf{Mon})$ is a diagram $\xymatrix{P_{X}\ar[r]^{\bar{k}}\ar[d]&P_{A}\ar@<.5ex>[r]^{\bar{p}}\ar[d]&P_{B}% \ar@<.5ex>[l]^{\bar{s}}\ar[d]\\ X\ar@<-.5ex>[r]_{k}&A\ar@<.5ex>[r]^{p}\ar@{-->}@<-.5ex>[l]_{q}&B\ar@<.5ex>[l]^% {s}}$ in which the lower row is a Schreier split epimorphism in $\mathbf{Mon}$, and the upper row consists of right normal submonoids, the positive cones $P_{X}$, $P_{A}$, and $P_{B}$, that make $X$, $A$, and $B$, objects in $\mathbf{Ord}\mathbf{Mon}^{*}$. The morphisms $\bar{k}$, $\bar{p}$, and $\bar{s}$, are the corresponding restrictions.
Definition 1. Given a monoid $A$ and a submonoid $M$ of $A$ we say that $M$ is - right normal if $a+M\subseteq M+a$, for every $a\in A$; - left normal if $M+a\subseteq a+M$, for every $a\in A$; - normal if it is both right and left normal.
Definition 2. We say that a monomorphism of monoids $m\colon{S\to A}$ is right normal if $m(S)$ is a right normal submonoid of $A$ and we denote by $\mathbf{RNMono}(\mathbf{Mon})$ the corresponding full subcategory of the category of monomorphisms of monoids, $\mathbf{Mono}(\mathbf{Mon})$.
Definition 4. Let $(X,P_{X})$ and $(B,P_{B})$ be two objects in the category $\mathbf{RNMono}(\mathbf{Mon})$. A preordered action of $(B,P_{B})$ on $(X,P_{X})$, that will be denoted by $(X,B,P_{X},P_{B},\varphi,\xi)$, consists of a monoid action of the underlying monoids $B$ on $X$, i.e. a monoid homomorphism $\varphi\colon{B\to\mathrm{End}(X)},$ together with a set-theoretical mapping $\xi\colon{X\times P_{B}\to X},$ satisfying the following conditions: (A1) $\xi(0,b)=0$, for all $b\in P_{B}$ (A2) if $x\in P_{X}$ then $\xi(x,0)=x$ (A3) if $\xi(x,b)=x$ and $\xi(x^{\prime},b^{\prime})=x^{\prime}$ then $\xi(x+b\cdot x^{\prime},b+b^{\prime})=x+b\cdot x^{\prime}$ (A4) for all $x,u\in X$, $v\in P_{B}$, $b\in B$, if $\xi(u,v)=u$, then there exists $u^{\prime}\in X$ such that $x+b\cdot u=u^{\prime}+v^{\prime}\cdot x$ and $\xi(u^{\prime},v^{\prime})=u^{\prime}$ where $v^{\prime}\in P_{B}$ is such that $b+v=v^{\prime}+b$, which exists because $P_{B}$ is right normal.
Definition 3.1. Let $I$ and $\mathcal{A}$ be $2$-categories, and let $F,G\colon I\to\mathcal{A}$ be $2$-functors between them. A lax-natural transformation $\mu\colon F\Rightarrow G$ comprises the data of (i) a morphism ${\mu_{i}}\colon{Fi}\rightarrow{Gi}$, for each $i\in I$, (ii) a $2$-morphism ${\mu_{f}}\colon{(Gf)\mu_{i}}\Rightarrow{\mu_{j}(Ff)}$, for each morphism $f\colon i\to j$ in $I$, $Fi$$Gi$$Fj$$Gj$$\mu_{i}$$Ff$$Gf$$\mu_{j}$$\mu_{f}$ which satisfy the following conditions: (1) for all $i\in I$, $\mu_{\operatorname{id}_{i}}=\operatorname{id}_{\mu_{i}}$, (2) for all composable morphisms $f,g$ in $I$, $\mu_{gf}=(\mu_{g}*Ff)(Gg*\mu_{f})$, (3) for all $2$-morphisms $\alpha\colon f\Rightarrow g$ in $I$, we have that $\mu_{g}(G\alpha*\mu_{i})=(\mu_{j}*F\alpha)\mu_{f}$. $Fi$$Gi$$Fj$$Gj$$\mu_{i}$$Fg$$Gf$$Gg$$\mu_{j}$$\mu_{g}$$G\alpha$$Fi$$Gi$$Fj$$Gj$$\mu_{i}$$Ff$$Fg$$Gf$$\mu_{j}$$\mu_{f}$$F\alpha$$=$ A pseudo-natural transformation is a lax-natural transformation ${\mu}\colon{F}\Rightarrow{G}$ whose every $2$-morphism component $\mu_{f}$ is invertible.
Definition 2.1. Let $F,G\colon I\to\mathcal{A}$ be $2$-functors. A $2$-natural transformation $\mu\colon F\Rightarrow G$ comprises the data of a morphism $\mu_{i}\colon Fi\to Gi$ of $\mathcal{A}$ for each $i\in I$, which must satisfy (1) for all morphisms ${f}\colon{i}\rightarrow{j}$ of $I$, we have $(Gf)\mu_{i}=\mu_{j}(Ff)$, and (2) for all $2$-morphisms ${\alpha}\colon{f}\Rightarrow{g}$ of $I$, we have $G\alpha*\mu_{i}=\mu_{j}*F\alpha$. $Fi$$Gi$$Gj$$\mu_{i}$$Gf$$Gg$$G\alpha$$Fi$$=$$Fj$$Gj$$\mu_{j}$$Ff$$Fg$$F\alpha$
Definition 5.3. Let $\mathcal{A}$ be a $2$-category. An object $L\in\mathcal{A}$ is bi-terminal if for all $X\in\mathcal{A}$ there is an equivalence of categories $\mathcal{A}(X,L)\mathrel{\simeq}\mathbbm{1}$.
Definition 2.7. Let $F\colon I\to\mathcal{A}$ be a $2$-functor. The strict-slice ${\Delta}\downarrow^{\textnormal{\tiny}}_{s}{F}$ of $2$-cones over $F$ is defined to be the following pullback in the ($1$-)category of $2$-categories and $2$-functors. ${\Delta}\downarrow^{\textnormal{\tiny}}_{s}{F}$$\mathcal{A}\times\mathbbm{1}$$[I,\mathcal{A}]\times[I,\mathcal{A}]$$[\mathbbm{2},[I,\mathcal{A}]]$$(\Delta,F)$$(s,t)$ This $2$-category ${\Delta}\downarrow^{\textnormal{\tiny}}_{s}{F}$ is given by the following data: (i) an object in ${\Delta}\downarrow^{\textnormal{\tiny}}_{s}{F}$ is a pair $(X,\mu)$ of an object $X\in\mathcal{A}$ together with a $2$-natural transformation $\mu\colon\Delta X\Rightarrow F$, (ii) a morphism $f\colon(X,\mu)\to(Y,\nu)$ consists of a morphism $f\colon X\to Y$ in $\mathcal{A}$ such that $\nu\Delta f=\mu$, (iii) a $2$-morphism $\alpha\colon f\Rightarrow g$ between morphisms $f,g\colon(X,\mu)\to(Y,\nu)$ is a $2$-morphism $\alpha\colon f\Rightarrow g$ in $\mathcal{A}$ such that $\lambda*\Delta\alpha=\operatorname{id}_{\mu}$. $\Delta X$$\Delta L$$F$$\Delta X$$F$$\mu$$\Delta f$$\Delta g$$\lambda$$\Delta\alpha$$=$ (2.8)
