Definition 5.1. Let $I$ and $\mathcal{A}$ be $2$-categories, and let $F\colon I\to\mathcal{A}$ be a $2$-functor. A bi-limit of $F$ comprises the data of an object $L\in\mathcal{A}$ together with a $2$-natural transformation $\lambda\colon\Delta L\Rightarrow F$ which are such that, for each object $X\in\mathcal{A}$, the functor ${\lambda_{*}\circ\Delta}\colon{\mathcal{A}(X,L)}\rightarrow{[I,\mathcal{A}](% \Delta X,F)}$ given by post-composition with $\lambda$ is an equivalence of categories. Similarly, we can define pseudo-bi-limit (resp. lax-bi-limit) by replacing $[I,\mathcal{A}]$ in the above with $\operatorname{Ps}[I,\mathcal{A}]$ (resp. $\operatorname{Lax}[I,\mathcal{A}])$.
Definition 2.9. Let $\mathcal{A}$ be a $2$-category. An object $L\in\mathcal{A}$ is $2$-terminal if for all $X\in\mathcal{A}$ there is an isomorphism of categories $\mathcal{A}(X,L)\cong\mathbbm{1}$.
