Definition 4.1. Let $I$ and $\mathcal{A}$ be $2$-categories, and let $F\colon I\to\mathcal{A}$ be a $2$-functor. (i) A pseudo-limit of $F$ comprises the data of an object $L\in\mathcal{A}$ together with a pseudo-natural transformation $\lambda\colon\Delta L\Rightarrow F$ such that, for each object $X\in\mathcal{A}$, the functor ${\lambda_{*}\circ\Delta}\colon{\mathcal{A}(X,L)}\rightarrow{\operatorname{Ps}[% I,\mathcal{A}](\Delta X,F)}$ given by post-composition with $\lambda$ is an isomorphism of categories. (ii) A lax-limit of $F$ comprises the data of an object $L\in\mathcal{A}$ together with a lax-natural transformation $\lambda\colon\Delta L\Rightarrow F$ such that, for each object $X\in\mathcal{A}$, the functor ${\lambda_{*}\circ\Delta}\colon{\mathcal{A}(X,L)}\rightarrow{\operatorname{Lax}% [I,\mathcal{A}](\Delta X,F)}$ given by post-composition with $\lambda$ is an isomorphism of categories.
Definition 21.4. A distance space $(X,d_{X})$ is defined to be • $(0)$-finitary (or else totally bounded) if $\mathbb{E}_{0}(X)\leq\omega$ (i.e., for any $\varepsilon\in(0,\infty]$ the entropy $\mathbb{E}_{\varepsilon}(X)$ is finite); • $(\infty)$-finitary if $\mathbb{E}_{\infty}(X)\leq\omega$ (i.e., $X$ has finitely many pseudometric components); • $(0,0)$-finitary (or else Assouad-bounded) if $\mathbb{E}_{0,0}(X)\leq\omega$ (i.e., there exists $\delta\in(0,\infty)$ such that for every $\varepsilon\in(0,\delta]$ the entropy $\mathbb{E}_{\varepsilon,\delta}(X)$ is finite); • $(0,\infty)$-finitary if $\mathbb{E}_{0,\infty}(X)\leq\omega$ (i.e., for any $\varepsilon,\delta\in(0,\infty)$ the entropy $\mathbb{E}_{\varepsilon,\delta}(X)$ is finite); • $(\infty,\infty)$-finitary (or else of bounded geometry) if $\mathbb{E}_{\infty,\infty}(X)\leq\omega$ (i.e., there exists $\varepsilon\in(0,\infty)$ such that for every $\delta\in(0,\infty)$ the cardinal $\mathbb{E}_{\varepsilon,\delta}(X)$ is finite).
Definition 24.1. A dimension controlling class $\mathcal{D}$ is called a dimension controlling scale if it satisfies the following conditions: • the identity function $(0,\infty)\to(0,\infty)$ belongs to $\mathcal{D}$; • for any functions $f,g\in\mathcal{D}$ the functions $f+g$ and $f\circ g$ belong to $\mathcal{D}$; • for any function $f\in\mathcal{D}$, any non-decreasing function $g\leq f$ belongs to $\mathcal{D}$.
Definition 4.2. We denote by $\mathsf{S}^{\infty}=(S^{\infty},\mu,\eta)$ the finitary monad on $\operatorname{\textnormal{$\mathbb{R}$-Vec}}$ induced by the strictly finitary monadic functor $U:C^{\infty}\kern-2.15pt\operatorname{\textnormal{-\text{Ring}}}\rightarrow% \operatorname{\textnormal{$\mathbb{R}$-Vec}}$. We call $\mathsf{S}^{\infty}$ the free $C^{\infty}$-ring monad on the category of real vector spaces.
Definition 2.7. If $(\mathcal{C},\otimes,k,\sigma)$ is an additive symmetric monoidal category with an algebra modality $(S,\mu,\eta,\mathsf{m},\mathsf{u})$, then an integral transformation on $\mathcal{C}$ is a natural transformation $\mathsf{s}$, with components $\mathsf{s}_{C}:SC\otimes C\to SC\;\;\;\;\;\;(C\in\mathcal{C})$ such that [s.1] Integral of a constant: $(\mathsf{u}\otimes 1)\mathsf{s}=\eta$; [s.2] Rota-Baxter rule: $(\mathsf{s}\otimes\mathsf{s})\mathsf{m}=[(\mathsf{s}\otimes 1\otimes 1)(% \mathsf{m}\otimes 1)\mathsf{s}]+[(1\otimes 1\otimes\mathsf{s})(1\otimes\sigma)% (\mathsf{m}\otimes 1)\mathsf{s}$]; [s.3] Interchange: $(\mathsf{s}\otimes 1)\mathsf{s}=(1\otimes\sigma)(\mathsf{s}\otimes 1)\mathsf{s}$. Such a $\mathcal{C}$ equipped with an integral transformation $\mathsf{s}$ is called a co-integral category.
Definition 2.1. An additive3Here we use the term additive category to refer to any category enriched in commutative monoids, while this term is more often used for categories that are enriched in abelian groups and have finite biproducts. symmetric monoidal category consists of a symmetric monoidal category $(\mathcal{C},\otimes,k,\sigma)$ such that $\mathcal{C}$ is enriched over commutative monoids and $\otimes$ preserves the commutative monoid structure in each variable separately.
Definition 5.3. For each $n\in\mathbb{N}$, define $\mathsf{d}_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}^{\flat}:C^{\infty}(\mathbb{R}^{n})\to C^{\infty}(% \mathbb{R}^{n})\otimes\mathbb{R}^{n}$ by $\mathsf{d}_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}^{\flat}(f):=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\frac{\partial f}{% \partial x_{i}}\otimes e_{i}$ where $e_{i}$ denotes the $i$-th standard basis vector for $\mathbb{R}^{n}$.
Definition 2.13. For a codifferential category with algebra modality $(\mathsf{S},\mu,\eta,\mathsf{m},\mathsf{u})$ and deriving transformation $\mathsf{d}$, define the following natural transformations [9], all of type $S\Rightarrow S$: (i) $\mathsf{L}:=\mathsf{d}\mathsf{d}^{\circ}$ (ii) $\mathsf{K}:=\mathsf{L}+S(0)$ (iii) $\mathsf{J}:=\mathsf{L}+1$. A codifferential category is said to have antiderivatives if $\mathsf{K}$ is a natural isomorphism.
Definition 6.9. Let $R$ be a commutative ring. A (commutative) Rota-Baxter algebra [12] (of weight $0$) over $R$ is a pair $(A,\mathsf{P})$ consisting of a commutative $R$-algebra $A$ and an $R$-linear map $\mathsf{P}:A\to A$ such that $\mathsf{P}$ satisfies the Rota-Baxter identity; that is, for each $a,b\in A$, the following equality holds: $\mathsf{P}(a)\mathsf{P}(b)=\mathsf{P}(a\mathsf{P}(b))+\mathsf{P}(\mathsf{P}(a)% b).$ The map $\mathsf{P}$ is called a Rota-Baxter operator.
Definition 2.3. If $(\mathcal{C},\otimes,k,\sigma)$ is a symmetric monoidal category, an algebra modality $(\mathsf{S},\mathsf{m},\mathsf{u})$ on $\mathcal{C}$ consists of: • a monad $\mathsf{S}=(S,\mu,\eta)$ on $\mathcal{C}$; • a natural transformation $\mathsf{m}$, with components $\mathsf{m}_{C}:SC\otimes SC\to SC$ $\>(C\in\mathcal{C})$; • a natural transformation $\mathsf{u}$, with components $\mathsf{u}_{C}:k\to SC$ $\>(C\in\mathcal{C})$; such that • for each object $C$ of $\mathcal{C}$, $(SC,\mathsf{m}_{C},\mathsf{u}_{C})$ is a commutative monoid (in the symmetric monoidal category $\mathcal{C}$); • each component of $\mu$ is a monoid morphism (with respect to the obvious monoid structures). Such an algebra modality $(\mathsf{S},\mathsf{m},\mathsf{u})$ will also be denoted by $(S,\mu,\eta,\mathsf{m},\mathsf{u})$ or by $\mathsf{S}$.
Definition 5.7. Using Lemma 5.6, we define $\mathsf{d}\;:\;S^{\infty}(-)\Longrightarrow S^{\infty}(-)\otimes(-)\;:\;% \operatorname{\textnormal{$\mathbb{R}$-Vec}}\rightarrow\operatorname{% \textnormal{$\mathbb{R}$-Vec}}$ to be the natural transformation $\mathsf{d}=\operatorname{\textnormal{{Lan}}}_{\iota}(\mathsf{d}^{\flat})\;:\;% \operatorname{\textnormal{{Lan}}}_{\iota}(C^{\infty})\Longrightarrow% \operatorname{\textnormal{{Lan}}}_{\iota}(C^{\infty}(-)\otimes(-))$ corresponding to $\mathsf{d}^{\flat}$ under the equivalence $\operatorname{\textnormal{{Lan}}}_{\iota}:[\operatorname{\textnormal{\text{Lin% }}}_{\mathbb{R}},\operatorname{\textnormal{$\mathbb{R}$-Vec}}]\rightarrow% \operatorname{\textnormal{\text{Fin}}}(\operatorname{\textnormal{$\mathbb{R}$-% Vec}},\operatorname{\textnormal{$\mathbb{R}$-Vec}})$ of Example 3.1.3 and Proposition 3.1.2. In view of Lemma 5.6.(2), we note that $\iota^{*}(\mathsf{d})=\mathsf{d}^{\flat}$ in the notation of Example 3.1.3, i.e., $\mathsf{d}_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}=\mathsf{d}^{\flat}_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}\;\;\;\;\;\;(n% \in\mathbb{N}).$
Definition 2.12. The coderiving transformation [9] for an algebra modality $(S,\mu,\eta,\mathsf{m},\mathsf{u})$ is the natural transformation $\mathsf{d}^{\circ}_{A}:SA\otimes A\to SA$ defined as follows: $\mathsf{d}^{\circ}:=(1\otimes\eta)\mathsf{m}$
Definition 2.9. A co-calculus category [9] is a codifferential category and a co-integral category on the same algebra modality such that the deriving transformation $\mathsf{d}$ and the integral transformation $\mathsf{s}$ satisfy the following: [c.1] The Second Fundamental Theorem of Calculus: $\mathsf{d}\mathsf{s}+S(0)=1$; [c.2] The Poincaré condition: if $f:B\to S(C)\otimes C$ is such that $f(\mathsf{d}\otimes 1)(1\otimes\sigma)=f(\mathsf{d}\otimes 1)$ then $f$ satisfies the First Fundamental Theorem; that is, $f\mathsf{s}\mathsf{d}=f$.
Definition 2.5. If $(\mathcal{C},\otimes,k,\sigma)$ is an additive symmetric monoidal category with an algebra modality $(S,\mu,\eta,\mathsf{m},\mathsf{u})$, then a deriving transformation on $\mathcal{C}$ is a natural transformation $\mathsf{d}$, with components $\mathsf{d}_{C}:SC\to SC\otimes C\;\;\;\;\;\;(C\in\mathcal{C})$ such that4Note that here, and throughout, we denote diagrammatic (left-to-right) composition by juxtaposition, whereas we denote right-to-left, non-diagrammatic composition by $\circ$, and functions $f$ are applied on the left, parenthesized as in $f(x)$; however, we write composition of functors in the right-to-left, non-diagrammatic order, and functors $F$ are applied on the left, as in $FX$. We suppress the use of the monoidal category associator and unitor isomorphisms, and we omit subscripts and whiskering on the right. [d.1] Derivative of a constant: $\mathsf{u}\mathsf{d}=0$; [d.2] Leibniz/product rule: $\mathsf{m}\mathsf{d}=[(1\otimes\mathsf{d})(\mathsf{m}\otimes 1)]+[(\mathsf{d}% \otimes 1)(1\otimes\sigma)(\mathsf{m}\otimes 1)]$; [d.3] Derivative of a linear function: $\eta\mathsf{d}=\mathsf{u}\otimes 1$; [d.4] Chain rule: $\mu\mathsf{d}=\mathsf{d}(\mu\otimes\mathsf{d})(\mathsf{m}\otimes 1)$; [d.5] Interchange5This rule was not in the original paper [4], but was later formally introduced in [5], and is used in [9]. It represents the independence of order of partial differentiation.: $\mathsf{d}(\mathsf{d}\otimes 1)=\mathsf{d}(\mathsf{d}\otimes 1)(1\otimes\sigma)$. Such a $\mathcal{C}$ equipped with a deriving transformation $\mathsf{d}$ is called a codifferential category.
Definition 2.9. Given an $\infty$-category $\mathcal{C}$ and an integer $d\geq-2$, we define the $d$-homotopy category of $\mathcal{C}$ to be $h_{d}\mathcal{C}$ of 2.8 when $d\geq 1$ and (1) For $d=-2$ we set $h_{-2}\mathcal{C}=\Delta^{0}$. (2) For $d=-1$ we set $h_{-1}\mathcal{C}=\begin{cases}\varnothing&\mathcal{C}=\varnothing\\ \Delta^{0}&\mathcal{C}\neq\varnothing\end{cases}$ with the unique map $\theta_{-1}\colon\mathcal{C}\to h_{-1}\mathcal{C}$. (3) For $d=0$, we first define a pre-ordered set $\tilde{h}_{0}\mathcal{C}$ with the same objects as $\mathcal{C}$ and the relation $x\leq y$ if and only if $\operatorname{Map}_{\mathcal{C}}\left(X,Y\right)\neq\varnothing$. Then we define $h_{0}\mathcal{C}$ to be the nerve of the poset obtained from $\tilde{h}_{0}\mathcal{C}$ by identifying isomorphic objects. There is a canonical map $\theta_{0}\colon\mathcal{C}\to h_{0}\mathcal{C}$ defined as the composition of $\theta_{1}\colon\mathcal{C}\to h_{1}\mathcal{C}$ with the nerve of the functor that takes each object in the homotopy category $h_{1}\mathcal{C}$ to its class in $h_{0}\mathcal{C}$ (with the unique definition on morphisms).
Definition 3.1. Let $d\geq-1$. An essentially $d$-operad is an $\infty$-operad $\mathcal{O}$ such that for all $X_{1},\dots,X_{n},Y\in\underline{\mathcal{O}}$, the multi-mapping space $\mbox{Mul}_{\mathcal{O}}\left(\left\{X_{1},\dots,X_{n}\right\};Y\right)$ is $\left(d-1\right)$-truncated. We denote by $\mathbf{Op}_{d}$ the full subcategory of $\mathbf{Op}_{\infty}$ spanned by essentially $d$ -operads.
Definition 3.6. Given an $\infty$-operad $p\colon\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}\to\mathbf{Fin}_{*}$, we define its $d$-homotopy operad $h_{d}\mathcal{O}$ to be a map of simplicial sets $p_{d}\colon\left(h_{d}\mathcal{O}\right)^{\otimes}\to\mathbf{Fin}_{*}$ defined as follows: (1) For $d\geq 1$, we simply apply $h_{d}$ to $p$ as a functor between $\infty$-categories and use the fact that $\mathbf{Fin}_{*}$ is a $1$-category; hence there is a canonical isomorphism $h_{d}\left(\mathbf{Fin}_{*}\right)\simeq\mathbf{Fin}_{*}$. (2) For $d=0$, we first construct the (ordinary) category $\tilde{h}_{0}\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}$ whose objects are those of $\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}$ and each mapping space is replaced by its image in $\mathbf{Fin}_{*}$. Then we identify isomorphic objects in $\tilde{h}_{0}\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}$ (note that there is a unique induced composition, since isomorphic objects are mapped to the same object in $\mathbf{Fin}_{*}$) and finally we define $\left(h_{0}\mathcal{O}\right)^{\otimes}$ to be the nerve of the resulting category, with $p_{0}$ being the obvious map to $\mathbf{Fin}_{*}$. (3) For $d=-1$, we define $p_{d}\colon\mathbf{Fin}_{*}\to\mathbf{Fin}_{*}$ to be the identity functor if $\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}\neq\varnothing$ and the unique functor $p_{d}\colon\varnothing\to\mathbf{Fin}_{*}$ otherwise.
Definition 2.1. For $d\geq 0$, a space $X\in\mathcal{S}$ is called $d$-truncated if $\pi_{i}\left(X,x\right)=0$ for all $i>d$ and all $x\in X$. In addition, a space is called $\left(-2\right)$-truncated if and only if it is contractible and it is called $\left(-1\right)$-truncated if and only if it is either contractible or empty. We denote by $\mathcal{S}_{\leq d}$ the full subcategory of $\mathcal{S}$ spanned by the $d$-truncated spaces. The inclusion $\mathcal{S}_{\leq d}\hookrightarrow\mathcal{S}$ admits a left adjoint and we call the unit of the adjunction the $d$-truncation map.
Definition 3.4. Let $\mathcal{O}$ be an $\infty$-operad. (1) For $d\geq 1$, we say that $\mathcal{O}$ is a $d$-operad if $\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}$ is a $d$-category. (2) We say that $\mathcal{O}$ is a $0$-operad if $\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}$ is a skeletal $1$-category and $p$ is faithful. (3) We say that $\mathcal{O}$ is a $(-1)$-operad if either $\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}=\varnothing$ or $p$ is an isomorphism.
Definition 2.6 (T.2.3.4.1). Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a simplicial set and let $d\geq-1$ be an integer. We will say that $\mathcal{C}$ is a $d$-category if it is an $\infty$-category and the following additional conditions are satisfied: (1) Given a pair of maps $f,f^{\prime}\colon\Delta^{d}\to\mathcal{C}$, if $f$ and $f^{\prime}$ are homotopic relative to $\partial\Delta^{d}$, then $f=f^{\prime}$. (2) Given $m>d$ and a pair of maps $f,f^{\prime}\colon\Delta^{m}\to\mathcal{C}$, if $f\mid\partial\Delta^{m}=f^{\prime}\mid\partial\Delta^{m}$, then $f=f^{\prime}$.
Definition 2.2. Let $d\geq-1$ be an integer. An essentially $d$-category is an $\infty$-category $\mathcal{C}$ such that for all $X,Y\in\mathcal{C}$, the mapping space $\operatorname{Map}_{\mathcal{C}}\left(X,Y\right)$ is $\left(d-1\right)$-truncated. We denote by $\mathbf{Cat}_{d}$ the full subcategory of $\mathbf{Cat}_{\infty}$ spanned by essentially $d$ -categories.
Definition 2.2. Let ${\mathcal{B}}$ be a bicategory. A 1-morphism $f:x\to{y}$ is called an equivalence if there exists a 1-morphism $g:y\to{x}$, and invertible 2-morphisms ${\mathrm{id}}_{x}\simeq g\circ{f},\quad f\circ{g}\simeq{\mathrm{id}}_{y}$
Definition 7.1. An algebra $A$ in ${\mathcal{C}}$ is an object equipped with a multiplication $m:A\otimes{A}\to{A}$ and a unit $u:1\to{A}$ satisfying the appropriate commutative diagrams.
Definition 3.10. Let $({\mathcal{B}},\otimes,\mathbf{1})$ be a symmetric monoidal bicategory. An object $x\in{\mathcal{B}}$ is dualisable if there exists $x^{*}\in{\mathcal{B}}$ and 1-morphisms $e:x\otimes x^{*}\to\mathbf{1}$ and $c:\mathbf{1}\to x^{*}\otimes{x}$ sastisfying the zig-zag identities up to 2-isomorphisms.
Definition 3.6. A 1-morphism $f:x\to{y}$ in ${\mathcal{B}}$ admits a right adjoint if there exists a 1-morphism $g:y\to{x}$, and 2-morphisms $\epsilon:f\circ g\to{\mathrm{id}}_{y}$ and $\eta:{\mathrm{id}}_{x}\to{g\circ{f}}$ satisfying the triangle identities.
Definition 4.2. A weak duality involution on ${\mathcal{A}}$ is the following collection of data: • a pseudofunctor $(-)^{\circ}:{\mathcal{A}}^{co}\to{\mathcal{A}}$; • a pseudonatural adjoint equivalence $\tikzcd{\mathcal{A}}\arrow[rr,equal,""{name=U,below}]\arrow[rd,"((-)^{\circ})^% {co}"^{\prime}]&&{\mathcal{A}}\\ &{\mathcal{A}}^{co}\arrow[Rightarrow,from=U,"\mathfrak{y}"]\arrow[ru,"(-)^{% \circ}"^{\prime}]&;$ and • an invertible modification $\zeta$, given in components by $\zeta_{x}:\mathfrak{y}_{x^{\circ}}\xrightarrow{\simeq}(\mathfrak{y}_{x})^{% \circ},\quad\forall x\in{\mathcal{A}}$ satisfying a compatibility diagram; see [17].
Definition 3.1. A linear category ${\mathcal{C}}$ is called finite if: • ${\mathcal{C}}$ has finite-dimensional vector spaces as spaces of morphisms; • every object of ${\mathcal{C}}$ has finite length; • ${\mathcal{C}}$ has enough projectives; and • there are finitely many isomorphism classes of simple objects.
Definition 3.12. A symmetric monoidal bicategory ${\mathcal{B}}$ is said to be fully dualisable if it admits duals for objects and 1-morphisms.
Definition 2.1. The Morita bicategory of algebras $\mathrm{Alg}_{2}$ is the bicategory where • the objects are finite-dimensional ${\mathbf{k}}$-algebras; • the 1-morphisms from $A$ to $B$ are finite-dimensional ${\mathbf{k}}$-vector spaces which are $(A,B)$-bimodules; and • the 2-morphisms are intertwiners of bimodules, i.e. ${\mathbf{k}}$-linear maps of bimodules which are compatible with the respective left and right actions of ${\mathbf{k}}$-algebras.
